{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16388"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16388"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.04,0.12,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9079"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9079"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"426"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5920"},{"type":"tags","id":"7192"},{"type":"tags","id":"7533"},{"type":"tags","id":"8844"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21576"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of gradually worsening vision in her right eye. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and spends long hours at a computer. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/60 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Fundoscopy reveals a pale, swollen right optic disc.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following visual field defects is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monocular scotoma","Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Superior quadrantanopia","Altitudinal hemianopia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of optic neuritis, characterised by unilateral vision loss and optic disc changes. Understanding the anatomy of the visual pathway is crucial for localising lesions based on visual field defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonocular scotoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the expected finding with an optic nerve lesion as it affects vision in only one eye. The optic nerve carries all visual information from a single eye, so any damage results in vision loss confined to that eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with lesions at the optic chiasm (such as pituitary tumours) where crossing fibres are affected, resulting in loss of temporal visual fields in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E results from lesions posterior to the optic chiasm (such as stroke affecting the optic tract, radiation, or occipital cortex), causing matching visual field defects in both eyes on the side opposite to the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with lesions in the temporal lobe affecting the inferior portion of the optic radiation (Meyer\u0027s loop), resulting in a contralateral superior quadrant defect in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAltitudinal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with ischaemic optic neuropathy, affecting either the superior or inferior half of the visual field in one eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Optic nerve lesions cause monocular vision loss or scotoma on the affected side.","Visual field defects from lesions beyond the optic chiasm cause homonymous deficits affecting both eyes.","The pattern of visual field loss helps localise lesions in the visual pathway."],"references":["Hoorbakht H, Bagherkashi F. Optic neuritis, its differential diagnosis and management. Open Ophthalmol J. 2012;6:65-72. doi: 10.2174/1874364101206010065. Epub 2012 Jul 24. PMID: 22888383; PMCID: PMC3414716.","Prasad S, Galetta SL. Approach to the patient with acute monocular visual loss. Neurol Clin Pract. 2012 Mar;2(1):14-23. doi: 10.1212/CPJ.0b013e31824cb084. PMID: 29443297; PMCID: PMC5766020.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16388"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60245"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T21:52:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:00:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9079"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"t